1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:19,000
Today is Tuesday, March 11, 2013. My name is John Dittmer and I'm here in Jackson, Mississippi, with videographer John Bishop.

3
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:25,000
To interview Mr. Euvester Simpson, a leading activist in the Civil Rights Movement in Mississippi.

4
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:33,000
This interview will become part of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, D.C.

5
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:39,000
Miss Simpson, we are delighted to be here today and we thank you for taking the time to talk with us.

6
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Let's begin by talking about your early life. Where were you born and raised?

7
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:58,000
I was born in the Mississippi Delta in Itta Bena, Mississippi and I lived there until I was about 14 years old on the youngest of seven children.

8
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:10,000
And during part of my parents' early marriage, my father was a butcher by trade.

9
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:18,000
But as times changed, part of their lives were spent as sharecroppers.

10
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:27,000
And when they had times that were good, they would leave the plantation and move to Greenwood, Mississippi.

11
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:34,000
And once they moved to Greenwood and several of my siblings were born when they actually lived in Greenwood.

12
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:46,000
My mother was originally from the Mound Bayou. She was born and lived and grew up until she was 18 on her grandfather's farm.

13
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:50,000
My great grandfather actually attended college.

14
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:56,000
And I think he must have been in that first generation after emancipation.

15
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:03,000
So he actually went to college. He was a teacher and he was a minister. he pastored a church and he owned a farm.

16
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:09,000
And my mother was born and she grew up there until she met my father.

17
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:16,000
And it's really funny. I have to tell this story if we have a minute to let me digress.

18
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:25,000
My mother once told me how she met my father. It was during revival at my great grandfather's church.

19
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
And my great grandfather owned a car. He actually bought a brand new car.

20
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:33,000
I think it was a Model T.

21
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:39,000
And it was the kind that she had to go at when you started it, you had to go crank it up.

22
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:45,000
So she had met my father during the course of the revival.

23
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:49,000
And within a few days he had convinced her to elope with him.

24
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:53,000
And she said, well, she was really not sure about it.

25
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:57,000
So she asked God to give her a sign if she wasn't supposed to do that.

26
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:05,000
So they went out and she had put on two of everything, two dresses, just doubled up because she knew she was ill-open.

27
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:09,000
And she went out and got in the car.

28
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:11,000
And my great grandfather, she called in Buddy.

29
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:13,000
And she said Buddy went out to start the car.

30
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:17,000
And he was cranking and cranking and it wouldn't start.

31
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:21,000
And she said, a brand new car. She said, that was my sign and I knew it.

32
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:25,000
But I ignored it anyway. I ignored that sign.

33
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:31,000
And so the next night the car started and elope with him.

34
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:39,000
And when my parents got married, they moved to a farm that was owned by a friend of my great grandfather's.

35
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:43,000
And that's where they set up their life at first.

36
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:51,000
And while they were living on that, this particular man owned a lot of acreage.

37
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,000
And he had many tenants on his land.

38
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:57,000
And so my parents rented land from him and they formed.

39
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:03,000
And life was good until later on when things changed.

40
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:09,000
And this man lost his land and my great grandfather lost his land somehow.

41
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:17,000
And then they had to do sharecropping and other things in order to make a living for a while.

42
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:23,000
And when I was maybe 10 or 11, they finally left the plantation and we moved.

43
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,000
We actually moved to Itta Bena, Mississippi.

44
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:34,000
And during those years, my oldest sister, I mean my only sister got married when I was nine years old.

45
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:38,000
And she moved to Chicago and I would spend summers with her.

46
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:46,000
And eventually, now I'm going to talk a little bit about how the school year, the school system was set up when I was growing up.

47
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:48,000
Yeah, please do.

48
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,000
And I'm not sure what year.

49
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
I attended elementary school at Ellis Rogers.

50
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:58,000
That was on the campus of Mississippi Valley State University.

51
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:06,000
And by the time, and then I, during the seventh grade, seventh through the ninth grade, I attended school.

52
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:10,000
That was in Itta Bena, Mississippi right across the street from where we lived.

53
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:19,000
And when I got to the tenth grade, the school system had, the school board had consolidated the entire school system.

54
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:27,000
And they built a brand new school where all the black kids had to be bust in from across the county.

55
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,000
And the name of that school was Amanda Elzy High School.

56
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:39,000
And the problem with that is that, you know, some of the kids, I mean, we, it took us about maybe 45 minutes to get to school to an hour.

57
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:46,000
But some of the kids lived in, you know, the far end of the counties and it took a long time for them to get there.

58
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:59,000
And so at that point, we had what they call a split session, where we would go to school in the middle of the summer so the kids could be out to pick cotton.

59
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:04,000
Or no, not chop, but pick cotton during the fall.

60
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:15,000
And so I was the last child that my parents were raising and they were just kind of fed up with, you know, with the way the educational system was working.

61
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:22,000
And so she talked to my older sister and they decided that I would move to Racine when I was 14.

62
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:27,000
So I moved to Racine to go to high school.

63
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:32,000
I would, yeah, that is, we, I want to spend some time on that with a contrast.

64
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:39,000
That was very interesting, weren't you, were saying, but you grew up in the Mississippi Delta with somebody called the most southern place on earth.

65
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,000
Tell us a little bit about what it was like to be in the Delta.

66
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:48,000
Let me have a sip of water.

67
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:56,000
My parents were like most of the people, most of the other people in my community, they were, you know, economically depressed.

68
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:03,000
It was totally segregated. All the schools were segregated. The neighborhoods were segregated.

69
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:12,000
Most of the people made their living by either sharecropping or hiring themselves out as day workers to go and chop and pick cotton.

70
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:19,000
And so there were the teachers and the preachers and some shop owners because everything was totally segregated.

71
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:31,000
You know, we, it was like a sufficient community. We had, you know, dry cleaners and of course there were lots of churches and beauty parlors and maybe a convenience store.

72
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:41,000
Or two because my pay at my father later in life, this is after, I must have been 17 or 18 or he opened a convenience store.

73
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:49,000
And he ran that little store. It was actually built right next to the house that they owned.

74
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:59,000
But in the earlier years, it was a very close knit community where everybody looked out for everybody else.

75
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:06,000
And one of the things, but of course nobody was, I mean, everybody knew their place.

76
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:12,000
I mean, they knew. But most of these people had at some point been independent.

77
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:21,000
And either them or their, their parents had owned land until probably somewhere around the 20s or the 30s.

78
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:34,000
Most people lost their land and that's when they became sharecroppers. And totally dependent on, you know, the white people who had the economic power and everything else.

79
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:42,000
And so their lives, they felt like they had no power except to do as they were, as they were told to do.

80
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:48,000
And this really confined economically depressed area.

81
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:56,000
So, what was, how did you spend your days when you were a kid? Did you, did you work in the fields? Did you?

82
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:04,000
Oh, I did a little bit, but I mean, I was really young. I tried to chop cotton.

83
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:11,000
Wasn't very good at cutting it all down and I wasn't allowed to do it anymore, which was fine with me because I'm not an outdoor.

84
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:18,000
Doorsy person, I can't stand bugs. It, I mean, being a country girl from the Delta, you would think I'd have no problems.

85
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:23,000
But I'm scared to death of all kinds of bugs and spiders and things.

86
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:32,000
And I was never, I tried to pick cotton. I think maybe once or twice I may have picked about 50 pounds and, you know, that was not going to cut it.

87
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:36,000
When there were people picking maybe three and four hundred pounds a cotton a day.

88
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:40,000
But you have to remember I was only, you know, I was a kid.

89
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:42,000
What did you do to have fun?

90
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Oh, I played with my friends, mud cakes, cooking and pretending to be, you know, cooking.

91
00:09:50,000 --> 00:10:03,000
And we didn't have very many toys. We only received toys at Christmas, you know. I got, I got one toy at Christmas and then lots and lots of food and fruits and nuts and things.

92
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:11,000
Now one thing, okay, I mentioned earlier that my father was a butcher by trade. So what that meant was that in the fall,

93
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:17,000
and now my brother just reminded me of this recently because I don't have a great memory of this.

94
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:27,000
But in the fall, all the neighbors would get my father to come around to their house and kill a hog or something.

95
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:33,000
And so if he was not paid, I don't think he was paid in money. He was probably paid in cuts of meat.

96
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:40,000
Because I remember once when we were living on a plantation, we actually had a smokehouse.

97
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:48,000
And once, I mean, we were not allowed in it. But there were, you know, I went in it and it just about scared me to death.

98
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:57,000
I saw all these great big hams hanging up and my mother made homemade sausages and so it was just packed full of that kind of stuff.

99
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:12,000
And when I was growing up, they also had huge gardens and with all kinds of fresh vegetables and in the fall, my mother would can or make, you know, dry peas and beans.

100
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:18,000
But there was all kinds of fruits and vegetables. Did your siblings end up in pitch-in with all the work on that?

101
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:25,000
Oh, yes, yes, everybody did. And I guess because I was the youngest, I mean, I didn't, I didn't have to do very much.

102
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:32,000
And my sister absolutely hated it. So, and all of them did not like farm, none of them like farm work.

103
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:38,000
And I have a brother who lives in Detroit now and he is, he's 81 years old.

104
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:46,000
So there was, you know, there was, my mother had like five kids and then there was a gap and then she had two more at the end.

105
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:50,000
And so I'm that last one that she had.

106
00:11:50,000 --> 00:12:01,000
But I was had a conversation with my brother. He came down here last year and he had before. He's still driving. He gets in his car and he drives down here and he gets around like he's 60.

107
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:08,000
So he was telling me that when he was like, okay, I have seven, there's seven of us and all.

108
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:19,000
I grew up with four with three other siblings or myself. So by the time I was three years old, my three older siblings were gone.

109
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:27,000
I just couldn't take any more. They left. And my brother, Sylvester, who lives in Detroit was telling me that when they first left home,

110
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:39,000
that they actually went to live with my grandparents for a while and they, my grandparents lived right outside of, it had been on a little community called Berclair, Mississippi.

111
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:53,000
And that's, and he told me that him and my older brothers, my other two brothers actually worked for the city of Greenwood. They, and they worked for the power company and I had no knowledge of this.

112
00:12:53,000 --> 00:13:01,000
They worked for the city of Greenwood. I think picking up garbage and actually driving the garbage truck.

113
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:14,000
So, and my family too is a part of, you know, the great migration. They went as soon as they were old enough. They all left and they went north and they worked in the auto industry.

114
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:24,000
And, you know, they would send boxes of clothes back and they'd expect, you know, because they all had good jobs and they bought property and they were going.

115
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:28,000
What were your aspirations? What did you want to do when you grew up?

116
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:33,000
Well, when I thought that I would become an actor, that's what I had a passion for.

117
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:36,000
Did you go to the movies a lot?

118
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:48,000
No, not really. Well, yeah, well, sometimes I went to the movies. But when I was in like the third grade, I, you know, I had the leading roles in the plays. Well, I was in the seventh grade.

119
00:13:48,000 --> 00:14:01,000
So, I got picked to have the leading role in the senior production. And now, what happened though? I probably would have had more experience as an actor as acting.

120
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:15,000
But when I left at 14 and I went to racing, it was a cultural shock. I went to a school that out of 2,000 kids there were maybe, like 10% of them were black, okay?

121
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:26,000
And, and so I joined the, the drama, the Dramatic Club and I never get picked. I picked four parts, you know, they were doing antigony and things like that.

122
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:38,000
And so I remember that the only part that I ever got was when we did Winnie the Pooh. I played the rabbit and Winnie the Pooh. Of course you were at all this makeup.

123
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:39,000
Yeah, yeah.

124
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:48,000
Everybody could tell what you are. Or anything. So that was a big disappointment. And so it was just a cultural shock for me to be.

125
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:53,000
And so, the teachers were white, even the janitors, the cooks in the, in the cafeteria.

126
00:14:53,000 --> 00:15:03,000
By the time you got there, you had seen things that none of your classmates have in the orphan scene. And I was just doing some statistical checking.

127
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:08,000
And the lynching of Emmett Till occurred when you were what, about 10 years old.

128
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:13,000
I was 10, I think I was been, let's see, that was 54. I was 9 years old.

129
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:18,000
And let me, oh, I can tell you about that. I remember we used to get the jet magazine.

130
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:25,000
And we, of course, we had heard about Emmett Till. I was the first one to get the magazine.

131
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:35,000
And I started flipping through it and I got to this page where this picture of him was, you know, oh, I just remember screaming and throwing it across the room.

132
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:40,000
And I never wanted to see it again. You know, it was just absolutely horrible. Just horrible.

133
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:44,000
This was the bloated corpse that, yes.

134
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:54,000
May, me tell, Emma's mother insisted that the coffin be open. And thousands of people filed by in Chicago and it became one of the most famous photographs.

135
00:15:54,000 --> 00:16:06,000
What, what was, what were your folks, you know, what, what kind of things do you remember what they were saying at the time? Did they give you, you know, it seems like every kid seemed like that they would think that could I be next?

136
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:23,000
Oh, we were all scared because we didn't know what was going to happen. You know, if they could kill, you know, a teenager for, you know, for something that, I mean, as minor as maybe looking at a white woman or trying to talk to her, we just didn't know what would happen.

137
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:31,000
And it was not long after that. It was either the year after I think the Reverend George Lee.

138
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:43,000
Yeah, talk about that. He was a friend of your father. He was a friend of my father's. Yeah. And my father was a member of the NAACP, but it was, it was just, you know, it's kept very quiet.

139
00:16:43,000 --> 00:17:00,000
Yeah. My father went to the funeral and a couple weeks or so after that, we, they, a newsletter was sent out. Maybe a month back that a newsletter of his, you know, with pictures of the funeral and all the proceedings and all.

140
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:10,000
It was, was, was mailed out and we were still living on a, on a plantation at that point because I was, yeah, nine years old, nine or 10.

141
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:17,000
And we were looking through that newsletter, trying to find, see if my father was in some of the pictures.

142
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:28,000
And we could not find a picture of him. And so we just put it aside. And then later, what have us picked it up? And there he was on the front cover of that.

143
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:34,000
And just looking down at the casket and somehow we lost that. That newsletter.

144
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:47,000
For the sake of the audience, the Reverend George Lee was very active in voting rights at that time and was gunned down. And of course, nobody was ever tried or convicted of his crime.

145
00:17:47,000 --> 00:18:01,000
The Brown decision saying that segregated schools were illegal, came out the year before and 54. Do you have any recollection of that and what it had no immediate impact in your area?

146
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:14,000
No, it had no immediate impact. I mean, things went on as they had always been we were still in segregated schools. I think maybe it did have some impact that we just, but not indirectly it was.

147
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:30,000
And there was some impact because that's right after that is when they built maybe right, you know, right at that, the school, the brand new elementary school that I attended starting in the third grade before then when the first school I went to was in a church.

148
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:36,000
And, you know, where they had two teachers, one for the little kids and one for the older students.

149
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:47,000
Yeah, that was the time that Mississippi legislature appropriated money to make separate but equal a fact thinking they could avoid desegregation. So a lot of schools got built.

150
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:54,000
Not too many laboratories, no libraries with books, but new buildings were built.

151
00:18:55,000 --> 00:19:03,000
Want to go to Wisconsin shortly, but tell me about the spiritual life was a church an important part of your family's life.

152
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:19,000
The church was very important. I mean, you know, they were like I said earlier, my parents were like everybody else. They were hard working church going people. You went to church every Sunday and then Sunday afternoon. You were back there for the BTU and whatever else.

153
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:39,000
And then, you know, Bible on Wednesday Bible study on Wednesday. I mean, the church was really important. But when early on when my parents lived in the country, they didn't have church in there, you know, the church that they were members of every Sunday because the minister lived somewhere else.

154
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:53,000
And so he would come every other Sunday to church, but the church was very important and I was it was a center of everything, you know, every social activity, just everything.

155
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:03,000
And that was the only place where people could feel like that they could express themselves and have and demonstrate their leadership abilities or whatever.

156
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:13,000
My father was was a Sunday school teacher. And I remember, you know, once we were living in Itta Bena, he became like one of the major Sunday school teachers.

157
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:33,000
And my mother would spend Saturdays because he loved to have his things all demonstrated. She would use and butcher block paper writing out and drawing his fun to school lessons. So he could demonstrate it on on Sunday. So yes, the church was was extremely important.

158
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:43,000
You said that they decided to send you to Wisconsin with your sister because they were just sort of getting that up with the school system and the divided.

159
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:49,000
This must have been a tough decision though to send your little girl your last away.

160
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:59,000
Well, it wasn't all that tough because like I said, I had spent, you know, I'd gone away this couple summers to live with my sister.

161
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:07,000
And they were coming back every summer to visit, you know. So I was a fairly easy decision for them.

162
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:22,000
I was the youngest one and they, you know, they were getting older and they wanted to want me to have a, you know, a good solid education. But it was always a temporary thing. I had always intended to come back and go to college.

163
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:27,000
Tell us that you were mentioning that Racine was much different. It was very different.

164
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:34,000
I was, it was, I would end for a culture shock when I, especially the school, you know, like I said.

165
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:51,000
Yeah. So Racine then was different than the Mississippi Delta. Talk about your experiences there, school, town, how it was to make that adjustment.

166
00:21:51,000 --> 00:22:00,000
Well, the major difference is that for the first time in my life, I actually, you know, interacted with white people.

167
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:09,000
I went to school with them because back in Mississippi, all the schools were totally segregated. But I actually, this was the first time.

168
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:27,000
And I actually had a few friends who were white at Washington Park High School. And the thing that was different about the school is that it was, I was just shocked that the, at all the, you know, the beautiful library, the equipment that they had.

169
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:41,000
And, and, you know, I was very athletic. So I, you know, I could, I played field hockey and soccer and, and I took tennis lessons and all that stuff.

170
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:53,000
And I was just, I did Tumblr and all of that stuff. And I'd never, I'd never been exposed to things like that. I just didn't even know that that kind of stuff existed, especially for high school.

171
00:22:53,000 --> 00:23:03,000
But the main shock was that if, you know, you're lucky if you had one other black kid and you're in a class with you.

172
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:14,000
And, but I got along very well. I mean, after a while, but I was really embarrassed to tell people that I was from Mississippi. I got teased about that, you know.

173
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:26,000
Well, I really didn't have an accent problem. It's just was just being from, from Mississippi, you know, and people call it, oh, Bigfoot country and all that.

174
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:33,000
So I just didn't help very many people that I was from Mississippi because I was just, I didn't want to be teased about it, you know.

175
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:48,000
But my, my sister was on her, had gotten onto her second marriage and so her husband at that point when I went to live with her, had a daughter who's about my age and she was my protector.

176
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:55,000
We went to school together and she knew everybody, you know, because she had lived there all of her life, well most of her life.

177
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:04,000
And so she was very helpful to me. Her name was Ruth, Ruth Days. And we became best friends.

178
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:15,000
Did you run into any segregation problems there? Or was it a unique experience to go into a restaurant and sit down and to counter and have a coke?

179
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:26,000
You know, and I don't think things were segregated in racing, you know, that, so we didn't have that kind of a problem.

180
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:35,000
The problem that I remember is that during the summers we didn't have much to do because the few jobs, you know, racing is not a really, really big town.

181
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:43,000
And maybe it's probably under 100,000. And the few jobs that teenagers could get all went to white kids.

182
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:52,000
So I remember there was an A&W Ruth beer not far from where we lived. And I wanted to work there, but of course they, I never got hired. I asked about.

183
00:24:52,000 --> 00:25:04,000
So the only work that I could get was babysitting for, you know, one of my sister's friends. And so that was, you know, in that regard there was not that much difference.

184
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:09,000
You came back during your senior year. I did.

185
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:13,000
I thought I would have thought you would have graduated up there and then come back.

186
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:31,000
You know, I wanted to go to college and my parents thought there may, and I'm not even sure about this, but we thought that there may be a problem without my graduating from a school out of the state and wanting to go to a public school,

187
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:39,000
because I was originally going to go to Valley State until after I got involved in the movement and, you know, found out about two balloon arms.

188
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:50,000
So they thought that there may be an issue with my graduating from an, you know, and having an address in Wisconsin and then trying to get into school here.

189
00:25:50,000 --> 00:26:01,000
So I came back and finished up my last semester at Amanda Elzy High School and that's the school that I originally had started the high school across the summer.

190
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:13,000
Well, while you were gone, we had a lot going on in Mississippi. You had the Freedom Rides, you had the Tougaloo sit-in, and you had the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee,

191
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:18,000
SNCC coming into McComb and then moving up to the Mississippi Delta.

192
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:35,000
So by the time you got back, a whole lot was going on in and around Greenwood, with voter registration campaigns, white violence, police dogs being set loose on demonstrators, the federal government sort of coming in, but not really doing much.

193
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:42,000
Tell us what it was like coming back into that and what motivated you to jump in with both feet.

194
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:57,000
Well, when I was in racing, I got involved with I joined the Youth Group Youth Chapter, the NAACP there, and we heard about what was going on down here, you know, with Meredith and the Freedom Rides and all of them.

195
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:10,000
We actually thought that we could get a bus and come down here as a bunch of about 20 students who were in, 20 of us who had been involved in the NAACP, but that just didn't happen.

196
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:26,000
So when I came back here in the winter in January of 1963, I mean things were going full blast because we hadn't been back here in a couple of years, so I didn't know what to expect.

197
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:43,000
But I mean the movement was in full force in Greenwood and in it, and then a friend of mine invited me to attend the mass meeting in Greenwood, and this must have been maybe around a couple of months before I got out of high school.

198
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:53,000
And when I got to that mass meeting, I tell you that it was just amazing what all the Freedom Songs and all these young people who were leading things.

199
00:27:53,000 --> 00:28:07,000
I mean, I think Hollis Watkins was there, Lawrence Guyot was there, John O'Neal, Mary Lane, and then I met my lifelong friend, June Johnson, and I became very close to June and her family.

200
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:20,000
But that night at that meeting, I knew that I had just found exactly what I was looking for, and that was the opportunity to work with people to change the conditions that we lived in.

201
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:26,000
All my life, I knew that I was not going to be living the kind of life that my parents lived.

202
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:29,000
And what did your parents think about your getting involved in it?

203
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:36,000
They were a little bit reluctant, you know, to let me get involved in it.

204
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:41,000
I'm going to tell you a story about what my father, he had a conversation with Longsky out.

205
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:52,000
When I told after I graduated high school, I told him I wanted to get involved full time in the movement until the fall when I could start college.

206
00:28:52,000 --> 00:29:03,000
So my father was really reluctant, he said, I'll tell you what, I'm going to go ahead and let you get involved, but you've got to give me the name of somebody who's in charge over there.

207
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:08,000
And I said, well, that's going to be kind of hard, because I don't know who's in charge.

208
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:12,000
It looks like there's no one particular person.

209
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:17,000
And I think my father said, well, I heard about this fellow named Lawrence Guyot.

210
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:21,000
And so he said, I'm going to call him, you give me his number.

211
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:23,000
My father found the number somehow.

212
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:28,000
And I didn't want him calling, telling somebody to be in charge of me and all that.

213
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:32,000
But anyway, when you were two later, I was in the SNCC office in Greenwood.

214
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:36,000
And Lawrence Guyot came up to me and he said, I got a call from your daddy.

215
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:39,000
I said, oh, don't tell me.

216
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:42,000
He said, and he put me in charge of you.

217
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:49,000
He told me that if anything happened to you, that I'm going to be, he's going to hold me responsible.

218
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:53,000
And he, I never let me forget that, never.

219
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:57,000
And you met Mrs. Fannie Lou Hamer about that time.

220
00:29:57,000 --> 00:29:59,000
I met Mrs. Hamer.

221
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:03,000
Relationship, your early relationship, impressions, friendship.

222
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:05,000
Okay.

223
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:07,000
I really got to know Mrs. Hamer.

224
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:09,000
I'd seen her around the office.

225
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:11,000
I'd seen her to sing in mass meetings.

226
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:18,000
But I really had not actually gotten really close to her until Annelle Ponder,

227
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:22,000
who was at that point with SCLC.

228
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:29,000
And she wanted a group of people to attend citizenship school in South Carolina.

229
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:33,000
And I was one of the ones who was selected.

230
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:41,000
Ms. Hamer and June Johnson and several other people were selected to go to the citizenship school.

231
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:43,000
Was a two week school.

232
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:48,000
And when we got to the bus station, so we were going to ride the bus over there.

233
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:50,000
Annelle Ponder set to us.

234
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:52,000
Can we stop on that?

235
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:53,000
Yeah, sure.

236
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:54,000
Okay.

237
00:30:54,000 --> 00:31:00,000
So when we were getting ready to leave,

238
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:05,000
and we left out of Greenwood to go to Charleston, South Carolina,

239
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:14,000
Annelle Ponder set to us, you know, I will be using the white side of the waiting room whenever we stop.

240
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:23,000
And because it's illegal for them to still have two separate waiting rooms and bus stations.

241
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:30,000
And she said, you don't have to do this because we're unlikely to get arrested for doing this,

242
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:33,000
especially when we're in Mississippi.

243
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:35,000
And I'm not saying that you have to do it.

244
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:41,000
I'm just telling you that if you want to, it's your choice, but I will be doing it.

245
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:51,000
And so on the way over there, whenever the bus stopped, we used the waiting room on the white side without any problems.

246
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:54,000
And we were over there for two weeks.

247
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:59,000
And Myles Horton was one of the people, you know, Myles Horton from the Highlander.

248
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:07,000
And Septima Clark was one of our teachers, and there was a man who was an Esau Jenkins,

249
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:10,000
and it was one of the instructors.

250
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:16,000
And that's Guy and Candie Carawan, Caroline during that time.

251
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:21,000
And we learned, just learned all the basics about what it meant to be a citizen.

252
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:25,000
What's your rights were, how important it was to vote.

253
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:34,000
And that was just demonstrating your rights as a citizen of this country.

254
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:39,000
The right to vote, the right to elect people, to represent you.

255
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:45,000
And what we were supposed to do from that information that we got from the Citizenship School

256
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:54,000
was to go back and help and have in conduct workshops to train other people on the importance of what it meant.

257
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:56,000
And it was your responsibility.

258
00:32:56,000 --> 00:33:03,000
It was our responsibility to be good citizens by getting people to register the vote.

259
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:12,000
And when you know, and to register ourselves and to actually, you know, to carry out and to do the things that, you know,

260
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:20,000
once you became a registered voter, and to carry out your civic responsibility as a citizen.

261
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:26,000
And with the SNCC project and voter registration, while you could just move right back into that with what you'd learned.

262
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:33,000
So by the time, see, at first, you know, SNCC was, was focused, I learned this later on direct action.

263
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:39,000
But by the time I got involved in the movement, the focus was on voter registration.

264
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:46,000
So that's what I got involved in, voter registration, a lot of canvassing, you know, the door to door in Greenwood.

265
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:52,000
June and I were always together walking the streets, she knew the area.

266
00:33:52,000 --> 00:34:00,000
And we walked the streets of Greenwood, you know, and we also went to, in my hometown, went to Itta Bena, Mississippi.

267
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:08,000
And, you know, people really didn't want to listen to me, especially the folks in my hometown, didn't want to listen to me about anything.

268
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:15,000
And they said, you know, we've been doing just fine, you know, the way we were, I think that they were really just afraid.

269
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:22,000
You know, it's not that they didn't want to my own parents, didn't register until, well, I was involved in movement.

270
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:28,000
And my involvement got, my activities got them involved.

271
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:36,000
And they, neither one of them had registered to vote on, you know, prior to my involvement in the movement.

272
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:42,000
They registered and they both, my father, who was a good bit older than my mother, was in his 60s.

273
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:44,000
I think in his 60s, the first time he voted.

274
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:49,000
And my mother was in her late 50s early 60s, the first time they voted.

275
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:57,000
And I will tell you from that time on until they die, they never missed the opportunity to vote.

276
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:06,000
Okay, tell us about the bus trip back from South Carolina, one of the most infamous journeys in the movement history.

277
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:17,000
Okay, we left. I can't remember what day of the week it was, but it was probably a weekend, like maybe a Friday.

278
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:32,000
So we all boarded the bus and we just made the assumption that we were going to repeat our activities of using the so-called white side of the waiting rooms every time we stopped.

279
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:35,000
And we did that several times.

280
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:43,000
And our last stop must have been in, I guess, an Alabama before we crossed the Mississippi line.

281
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:47,000
And we got to Winona, Mississippi and we got off the bus several times.

282
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:49,000
This was pretty near home, wasn't it?

283
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:52,000
We were pretty near home and we thought, okay, we're almost home now.

284
00:35:52,000 --> 00:35:55,000
So no incidents, nothing happened. We're okay.

285
00:35:55,000 --> 00:36:02,000
And without even thinking about it, several of us got off the bus and we went to use the restroom.

286
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:13,000
But before we could even get inside, there were car loads of highway patrolmen and local police there.

287
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:17,000
And they ordered us out and we refused to leave.

288
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:27,000
And so they just grabbed us and threw all of us in the back seat of one car.

289
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:30,000
And we just piled us in on top of each other.

290
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:36,000
And Mrs. Hamer was one of the people who did not get off the bus initially.

291
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:54,000
When she saw us being arrested, she got off the bus as fast as she could and said, oh, well, I know when they started first arresting us, thrown us in Annelle Ponder, pulled out a pad, and started writing down the license plate number.

292
00:36:54,000 --> 00:37:03,000
And at that point, they just threw everybody in and then Miss Hamer came up, got off the bus and says, what is going on?

293
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:06,000
What are y'all doing? Why are you arresting them?

294
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:09,000
And they threw her in to the car too.

295
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:14,000
And when we got to the jail,

296
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:19,000
and I guess we went to the city jail of County jail, I'm not sure where we were.

297
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:25,000
When we got there, the jailer didn't quite know what to do with us.

298
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:32,000
There was me and Mrs. Hamer and Annelle Ponder and June Johnson.

299
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:38,000
And I think Rosemary from that I'm not sure the makeup of the group.

300
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:44,000
But Annelle Ponder was the spokesperson and she got asking questions.

301
00:37:44,000 --> 00:37:46,000
And of course, they called her.

302
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:51,000
She was an older person, right? And college educators, then very professional.

303
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:57,000
Very professional, very soft spoken, very articulate.

304
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:01,000
And she kept asking why have they arrested us?

305
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:04,000
And she said, you know, what have we done wrong?

306
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:12,000
And that there was a, you know, we were not violating any laws because the ICC was at the innards.

307
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:18,000
Commerce commission had already passed this law that it was illegal to have separate waiting rooms.

308
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:22,000
And we were just exercising our rights as citizens, you know.

309
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:25,000
And it was very lawful.

310
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:30,000
But the jailer just kept telling her to shut up.

311
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:34,000
And then she said something to him.

312
00:38:34,000 --> 00:38:37,000
And now he asked her a question and she said no.

313
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:43,000
And she, he wanted her to say no sir or yes sir.

314
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:45,000
And she said, well, I'm not going to say that.

315
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:47,000
She said, I'll answer your question.

316
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:50,000
But I'm not going to say yes sir, a no sir.

317
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:54,000
And at that point, he just, you know, he started hitting her.

318
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:57,000
And what he did to me.

319
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:01,000
And then I spoke up and said, because that's what I had no fear.

320
00:39:01,000 --> 00:39:02,000
I don't know.

321
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:03,000
I mean, what?

322
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:04,000
You were just a kid.

323
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:05,000
I was a kid.

324
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:19,000
And I had never really, you know, had a confrontation with any white person that, you know, I've never seen the kind of meanness and just evilness that, you know, that I witnessed then.

325
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:22,000
And so, but I still wasn't afraid.

326
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:24,000
So I said something.

327
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:25,000
And the jailer took it.

328
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:29,000
So he had this huge, I don't know if it was his huge ring of keys.

329
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:37,000
And he took him and he jabbed him in my side and stumped my foot and just told me to shut up.

330
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:41,000
And I was going to keep on talking and Annelle Ponder just said, that's okay.

331
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:42,000
Don't say anything else.

332
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:44,000
And then they put us all in sales.

333
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:48,000
And so I was, I shared, they had, they had a row of sales.

334
00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:53,000
And so the very first sale was left empty.

335
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:55,000
And Miss Hamer and I were in the next one.

336
00:39:55,000 --> 00:39:59,000
And then June Johnson and the nail were on down the line.

337
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:03,000
Annelle Ponder ponder was the first person that they took out.

338
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:13,000
And since Miss Hamer and I were in the sale right next to the empty one, what they did was that they took us into,

339
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:17,000
they would take you into a sale, that empty sale.

340
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:23,000
And make you lie on a cot and there were two trustees who were there.

341
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:25,000
And they were, you could smell the alcohol on them.

342
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:29,000
They really didn't want to do what they were doing.

343
00:40:29,000 --> 00:40:34,000
But they made them drink and then they were, they told them to be it.

344
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:39,000
So you had to lie on this cot in that sale.

345
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:45,000
And I could just hear them, you know, hitting, that this huge strap.

346
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:50,000
And it seems to me it had holes in it or it had something attached to it.

347
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:57,000
And they were, I could hear Annelle Ponder just kind of mown and she didn't scream out a lot.

348
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:02,000
But and then finally they let, they brought her back and they let her pass us.

349
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:05,000
And I could see that her, you know, her face was bloody.

350
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:08,000
She was bleeding, her dress was torn.

351
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:10,000
And then she took June out.

352
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:16,000
June was a, you know, didn't look, June was only 14, I was sending June was tall girl.

353
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:20,000
And she looked older, she asked the matter fact, she looked older than I did.

354
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:24,000
And so they took her out and then the same thing happened with June.

355
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:28,000
Then they took Miss Hamer out.

356
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:29,000
And she was in your sale?

357
00:41:29,000 --> 00:41:32,000
She was in my sale.

358
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:36,000
And oh boy, they really worked her over.

359
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:42,000
And she just hear her, her screaming and screaming and just, you know, asking them to please stop.

360
00:41:42,000 --> 00:41:44,000
And she said, you know, why are you doing this?

361
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:48,000
She said, you, you are just like me, you know, you're, you're black like me.

362
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:50,000
So why are you, why are you beating me?

363
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:54,000
And they just, they kept going at it and finally they brought her back.

364
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:59,000
And then they took me out and took me to that sale.

365
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:03,000
And they made me lie on this cot.

366
00:42:03,000 --> 00:42:07,000
And they raised a strap up and just hit me one time.

367
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:11,000
And at that point, the jailer came in and said, stop.

368
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:14,000
Take her back to her sale.

369
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:18,000
So we're thinking at what happened by that time, is that?

370
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:21,000
Because two people, one or two people had been left on the bus.

371
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:26,000
And they had gone back to Greenwood and they told everybody what was going on.

372
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:30,000
And so they immediately started calling and looking, trying to find us.

373
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:38,000
And I think what happened by that time, Lawrence Guyot also had probably made it to wine on it.

374
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:40,000
But they arrested him. We never saw him.

375
00:42:40,000 --> 00:42:44,000
They arrested Lawrence Guyot really beating him up, really, really badly.

376
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:48,000
And, you know, I didn't think about this until later.

377
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:52,000
I said, I wonder if one of the reasons that Lawrence Guyot was so adamant.

378
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:54,000
I mean, he was that kind of a person anyway.

379
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:57,000
He had promised my father that nothing would happen to me.

380
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:01,000
And so he said, oh my God, I've got to get that girl all the time.

381
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:04,000
You mean worse than face than your father than the sheriff?

382
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:06,000
No, no.

383
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:12,000
So Lawrence Guyot was beaten and so they brought me back to the sale in his hammer.

384
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:15,000
By this time, I'm thinking it must have been Sunday.

385
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:17,000
It was Sunday night.

386
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:20,000
And Miss Hamel was in such pain.

387
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:23,000
Her hands were all black and blue and swollen.

388
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:27,000
And her buttocks were all swollen and hard.

389
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:29,000
And she developed a fever.

390
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:31,000
And the only thing I had was a washcloth.

391
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:36,000
And we had a sink there which, you know, I put, kept putting cold water on it.

392
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:40,000
And, you know, and putting it on her forehead trying to bring a fever down.

393
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:44,000
And we, we didn't get any sleep, of course, that night.

394
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:50,000
And so what we did do, I mean, we decided, you know, when she calmed down a bit and the pain wasn't so bad,

395
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:55,000
we decided that we would sing some, some songs.

396
00:43:55,000 --> 00:43:56,000
And Miss Hamel.

397
00:43:56,000 --> 00:43:58,000
I had no idea what that's news to me.

398
00:43:58,000 --> 00:43:59,000
Yes, we did.

399
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:02,000
We decided to sing a bit.

400
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:05,000
And we did, just, you know, a few songs we didn't sing all night,

401
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:08,000
but we did it quietly, you know, for ourselves.

402
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:12,000
And one of Miss Hamel's, of course, her signature song is this little light of mine.

403
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:17,000
We didn't, but she wanted to do the gospel songs.

404
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:24,000
And one of her favorite songs, her gospel songs is, if I can remember the name of it, walk with me.

405
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:26,000
And we did that one.

406
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:29,000
And it was just powerful and it calmed her down.

407
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:36,000
And it was like, you know, walk with me, Lord, please, this is going to make me cry.

408
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:37,000
It's okay.

409
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:39,000
So, I'll stop.

410
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:40,000
Okay.

411
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:42,000
It's...

412
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:45,000
Okay.

413
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:48,000
Can we stop on that?

414
00:44:48,000 --> 00:44:51,000
Snick knew that you were there.

415
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:55,000
They had people calling the jail, lawyers calling the jail.

416
00:44:55,000 --> 00:45:00,000
And did that have an impact on how you were treated from that time on?

417
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:05,000
Well, I think it did, because there were no more beatings.

418
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:07,000
And we did.

419
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:11,000
We were roused one night.

420
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:13,000
And we didn't know.

421
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:19,000
They talked about moving us, because I think that they thought that people knew where we were.

422
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:23,000
And they weren't quite ready to let us go.

423
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:26,000
So, they talked about moving us in the middle of the night.

424
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:30,000
And we decided, and now decided, that we were not going to go anywhere.

425
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:37,000
We were really going to just, because we didn't want to be taken out somewhere in the middle of the night, and, you know, and disappear forever.

426
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:46,000
So, Annelle Ponder was really very outspoken at that point, and told them that, you know, that we're not going anywhere.

427
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:48,000
And we're not going to take us anywhere.

428
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:50,000
And so, they decided not to do that.

429
00:45:50,000 --> 00:45:52,000
And they put us back in ourselves.

430
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:53,000
And I'm just...

431
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:59,000
I'm telling you, I don't remember much of what happened after...

432
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:03,000
We were arrested, I think, maybe on a Sunday.

433
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:07,000
We stay there, maybe until Wednesday.

434
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:14,000
Or so, and I don't have a lot of recollection of the day-to-day activities of what happened.

435
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:29,000
And then, I think there was on Wednesday, Andrew Young, and there was someone else who came with him to get us out of jail.

436
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:35,000
He informed us that the first thing he told us, he said, I've got some sad news.

437
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:38,000
And I'm pretty sure this is right, this is accurate.

438
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:44,000
He told us that Medgar Evers had been killed, and assassinated the night before.

439
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:55,000
And he said he had left a meeting in Jackson, and he was on his way home, and he'd been ambushed and killed.

440
00:46:55,000 --> 00:47:01,000
And so, you know, the joy of getting out was just totally overshadowed.

441
00:47:01,000 --> 00:47:05,000
I really didn't know Matt here. I knew who he was.

442
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:09,000
But it was just a sad, sad day.

443
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:14,000
Well, for a lot of people, that would have been an indication it's time to get out.

444
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:19,000
I paid my dues, let somebody else...what was your attitude after that?

445
00:47:19,000 --> 00:47:22,000
My attitude was that I was just getting started.

446
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:33,000
You know, I'm 17 years old, and I'm home, and this made me more determined to stay involved.

447
00:47:33,000 --> 00:47:36,000
And that was Miss Hamas attitude, too.

448
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:40,000
I mean, she said, I'm not going to let this scare me off.

449
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:46,000
And so, that's when I think that time and the one on the jail for all of us,

450
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:51,000
especially for Miss Hamas, it was like a watershed event.

451
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:53,000
It was a turning point for her.

452
00:47:53,000 --> 00:48:01,000
And after that, it's when she really came into her own, and she became a national, you know, just a national figure.

453
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:06,000
And that great voice of hers singing and speaking everywhere.

454
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:10,000
And she told the story of Winona, Mississippi at the Democratic National Convention,

455
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:13,000
a year later, with an audience of millions.

456
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:17,000
And it was the dramatic point of the entire convention.

457
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:21,000
There was a trial held in Oxford, and you attended?

458
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:23,000
I did.

459
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:27,000
There were people who were charged, talk a little bit about that.

460
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:30,000
That's sort of a footnote, but interesting, I think.

461
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:37,000
You know, during that trial, they got our story, okay?

462
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:42,000
We were in Oxford for maybe, for several days, or probably about a week.

463
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:49,000
And when I took the witness stand, because we were not allowed to hear anybody else's testimony,

464
00:48:49,000 --> 00:48:55,000
when I took the witness stand, I was simply asked just a couple of questions.

465
00:48:55,000 --> 00:48:57,000
I mean, was I arrested?

466
00:48:57,000 --> 00:49:02,000
I said, yes, was I beaten while I was in jail?

467
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:09,000
And so, my answer was no, because I got one litre with a strap.

468
00:49:09,000 --> 00:49:16,000
And they gave me no opportunity to explain about what I heard, what I saw.

469
00:49:16,000 --> 00:49:20,000
They only wanted to know what happened to me.

470
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:24,000
So, I don't really know much about what went on.

471
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:27,000
We were, like I said, we were not allowed to hear anybody else's testimony.

472
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:33,000
And you were just kept away, and I spent maybe less than five minutes on the witness stand.

473
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:36,000
Well, it seemed like the prosecutor, if you can say that,

474
00:49:36,000 --> 00:49:39,000
would have been more interested in getting your story out.

475
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:42,000
No, that was not the case.

476
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:48,000
I was not allowed to elaborate on anything.

477
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:55,000
And I think they seized on the, what I said, no, I was not, I mean, I don't call,

478
00:49:55,000 --> 00:50:01,000
look, when I heard what happened to the other people, and the length of time they were beaten,

479
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:05,000
what I got, I thought was the least of it.

480
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:10,000
But I'd never had the opportunity to explain that.

481
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:17,000
Things were starting to happen rapidly in Mississippi then, in the fall of 1964,

482
00:50:17,000 --> 00:50:23,000
COFO, which was the umbrella organization of SNCC and CORE and local NAACP

483
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:27,000
and other local groups operating under the COFO banner.

484
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:35,000
I decided to have a freedom vote to dramatize to the country that blacks would vote if given the opportunity.

485
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:40,000
Tell us about that campaign and your involvement in it.

486
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:46,000
Well, you know, I think it had been a long held belief that the black people didn't want to have anything to do with politics.

487
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:51,000
And they would, we wouldn't vote, even if we were given the opportunity to vote.

488
00:50:51,000 --> 00:51:08,000
But that campaign was, I mean, just proved everything that the power structure was saying about what black people wanted and what we would do.

489
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:10,000
I got involved in it.

490
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:18,000
And one of the things that I did, though, I mean, from as a result of my citizenship trade, and I had other training too,

491
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:24,000
I, I know I went to Clarksdale, Mississippi and I went to another place.

492
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:33,000
And I actually did mock, you know, present workshops, you know, dramatizing what could possibly happen.

493
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:41,000
At this point, I'm 18 years old and I remember Aaron E. Henry arranged me for me to come to his church and come to his place.

494
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:44,000
He was the candidate for governor on the ticket.

495
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:47,000
We held workshops at his church.

496
00:51:47,000 --> 00:51:50,000
And there was another woman who's house I stayed at Miss Piggy.

497
00:51:50,000 --> 00:51:54,000
And it was just, it was just a lot of fun conducting those workshops.

498
00:51:54,000 --> 00:51:59,000
And you know, people just got really, really involved in their roles and all.

499
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:07,000
And what I know, I mean, the results of it is that there was just a huge turnout and people voted.

500
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:14,000
And of course, it didn't really, we couldn't really actually vote because people weren't registered.

501
00:52:14,000 --> 00:52:24,000
But they'd show that people had a lot of interest in politics and being able to exercise their right as citizens.

502
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:26,000
So all this happened.

503
00:52:26,000 --> 00:52:30,000
There was some publicity nationally, not a whole lot.

504
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:41,000
But a lot of the publicity was devoted to a group of white college students who came down from Yale and Stanford to assist in that campaign.

505
00:52:41,000 --> 00:52:56,000
And although the SNCC had been active in Mississippi for several years now, why the white supremacists were still in control, you now had a revived Ku Klux Klan that was beginning to move.

506
00:52:56,000 --> 00:53:00,000
And the federal government was not very helpful.

507
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:18,000
So you had discussions in SNCC and COFO about maybe having a summer project where you invite hundreds of people down from the North to work in local communities in part to dramatize the plight of blacks in Mississippi.

508
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:21,000
But also maybe to force the federal government to take action.

509
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:25,000
Were you part of those discussions because they became rather heated at times?

510
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:35,000
Well, I tell you what, I was not, you know, I'm 17 years old and I didn't do a lot of talking.

511
00:53:35,000 --> 00:53:52,000
I was there at the meetings and I basically agreed with what many people were saying because the logic of it was that if the federal government didn't seem to care much about what happened to black people,

512
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:56,000
we were still being killed and still being the not the right to vote.

513
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:13,000
But if we brought down the children of affluent people from different parts of the country, and if they received the same kind of treatment that we had been getting, then, you know, the whole country is going to pay attention.

514
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:16,000
And that is exactly what happened.

515
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:28,000
You know, when they started being arrested and beaten and killed, I remember that I was a part of the, I did go to Oxford for the summer orientation.

516
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:31,000
What did you tell us about that? That's a very interesting part.

517
00:54:31,000 --> 00:54:37,000
Well, unfortunately, I mean, my mother took sick, what I was saying.

518
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:41,000
I left after a day. I had to come back home.

519
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:44,000
And you were there the first week?

520
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:48,000
I was there. I left after a couple of the two or three days.

521
00:54:48,000 --> 00:55:01,000
And there were workshops demonstrating to people what could possibly happen to you and demonstrating the non-violent techniques of how to protect yourself, you know, if things happen.

522
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:14,000
And they were, you know, of course, they were dramatized and they were like, you know, overdone to give people a sense of what could possibly happen and what you have to do in case these things happen.

523
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:19,000
Because they could actually get to the point where you could be beaten and worse killed.

524
00:55:19,000 --> 00:55:33,000
And before I left, though, we got word that James Chaney and Michael "Mickey" Schwerner and The three Freedom Summer victims, I had not met Andrew because he was one of the summer volunteers going down.

525
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:41,000
And he left early from the orientation to go back to Meridian with Michael "Mickey" Schwerner and with James.

526
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:46,000
So I've never met him. I later met his mother.

527
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:57,000
As a matter of fact, when we were working on the 30th reunion for Freedom Summer, she came down and was a part of that.

528
00:55:57,000 --> 00:56:10,000
So you came back and the summer begins with the news. The three civil war rights workers have disappeared and everybody understood that they were dead.

529
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:19,000
Tell us about that summer and your role in it, your recollections of what went on.

530
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:34,000
By this point, okay, in the fall of 1963, instead of going to college, I actually moved to Jackson because I had spent the summer working voter registration in Greenwood and Greenville.

531
00:56:34,000 --> 00:56:44,000
And the spring of 1964, I was in Hattiesburg and McComb, you know, doing voter registration.

532
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:46,000
With the Freedom Days there?

533
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:58,000
Yes. And then in the spring of 1964, I was in Jackson and so I started working in the COFO Office.

534
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:08,000
And the first time the COFO Office was up and running and as you know that it was made up of SNCC and CORE and the NAACP and SCLC.

535
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:16,000
We all shared a space at this Council of Federated Organizations and we shared this space there.

536
00:57:16,000 --> 00:57:22,000
And we had what we called Long Before Cellphones, the WATS line.

537
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:35,000
And one of the things that I did was I learned how to use the WATS line and we had to have somebody staff at watch line 24 hours a day, you know, in case somebody called in.

538
00:57:35,000 --> 00:57:48,000
And the WATS line was there so that if somebody got in trouble and you know they needed to get the word out that they were in trouble wherever they were across the state.

539
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:55,000
And they didn't have access to, you know, they have money to pay for a phone or something to get to a pay phone.

540
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:01,000
They could maybe use somebody's phone and call in and relay the message.

541
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:03,000
And they were supposed to check in every day.

542
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:06,000
They were supposed to check in anyway, every day.

543
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:12,000
And so that's why we had to have staff there, manning that telephone 24 hours.

544
00:58:12,000 --> 00:58:15,000
And the part of what I did was I took a shift.

545
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:19,000
I was not out in the field working and during the summer.

546
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:23,000
But everybody at some point came through the Jackson office.

547
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:28,000
So I met most of the people who were down that summer.

548
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:33,000
Who else is working in the office with you?

549
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:39,000
Well, one of the people was the person that I finally married.

550
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:43,000
Jesse Moore, he's the father of my five children.

551
00:58:43,000 --> 00:58:45,000
And he had come in from California.

552
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:47,000
Right, exactly.

553
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:53,000
So he was one of the people actually, you know, Jesse and Bob and Dave were...

554
00:58:53,000 --> 00:58:56,000
Bob Moses and Dave Dennis.

555
00:58:56,000 --> 00:59:03,000
Bob Moses and Dave Dennis were actually, you know, kind of in short, well they shared responsibilities with one in the summer project.

556
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:11,000
And I'm trying to remember, oh, who else was in that office?

557
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:15,000
I met Gwen Gillon that summer.

558
00:59:15,000 --> 00:59:17,000
She worked because she was a student.

559
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:19,000
She's from Alabama.

560
00:59:19,000 --> 00:59:20,000
And she was a student, yeah.

561
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:21,000
And she was a student, yeah.

562
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:22,000
And I met her.

563
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:28,000
Well, I actually met Gwen, I guess, in maybe India, maybe the spring of 1964.

564
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:31,000
And we became really, really good friends.

565
00:59:32,000 --> 00:59:33,000
I'm trying to remember who else.

566
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:35,000
There were several people who were...

567
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:39,000
I'm trying to remember if Mary King was there, Casey Hayden.

568
00:59:39,000 --> 00:59:46,000
And these were young white women from the South who had been active and snick for a while.

569
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:47,000
Right, right.

570
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:51,000
Dona Richards Moses Moses, who at one point was a Dona Richards Moses Moses.

571
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:55,000
She and Bob were married.

572
00:59:56,000 --> 01:00:03,000
And I'm trying... I don't remember who else was working in that office across the summer though.

573
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:06,000
Did you ever come across Worth Long?

574
01:00:06,000 --> 01:00:07,000
Oh, yes, yes.

575
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:10,000
You heard any stories about Worth Long his friend's life?

576
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:12,000
Oh, Worth Long his friend's of yours.

577
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:15,000
Well, Worth Long used to come to town.

578
01:00:15,000 --> 01:00:22,000
And he stayed at a house many a nights, you know, whenever he would come through and need a place to stay.

579
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:29,000
And Worth Long was really involved in... he was an oral historian.

580
01:00:29,000 --> 01:00:36,000
He liked to go out in the countryside and just talk to regular people and find out what was going on.

581
01:00:36,000 --> 01:00:44,000
And I remember later he was instrumental in getting the Blues Festival up in the Delta Blues Festival.

582
01:00:44,000 --> 01:00:49,000
And he did a lot of... arranged a lot of the documentation for the Blues Festival.

583
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:55,000
So he was kind of a folklorist and he... that's what I remember about Worth Long.

584
01:00:55,000 --> 01:01:02,000
And I saw him recently at... and I was just surprised to see him because I knew Worth Long it had been sick.

585
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:04,000
But I saw him at the Cofo office.

586
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:08,000
There was something going on just a few months ago I believe.

587
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:10,000
And so it was really good to see him.

588
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:14,000
I thought him and said he's been feeling better the last year.

589
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:19,000
So it was really good to see him up and about.

590
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:21,000
Anything stand out in the summer?

591
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:25,000
Incidents? Things you were involved in? Violence?

592
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:33,000
Well, there was always... there's, you know, violence all over the state being reported.

593
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:38,000
And I'm just... I'm trying to remember this has been 50 years ago, John.

594
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:42,000
And it's... I'm trying to remember details if you want to ask me about...

595
01:01:42,000 --> 01:01:48,000
There was something... well, there was something that I came across about...

596
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:55,000
You're going to a movie as a Lamar theater or... or downtown and...

597
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:57,000
Oh, really?

598
01:01:57,000 --> 01:01:58,000
Yeah, now I...

599
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:00,000
What did I go to see?

600
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:03,000
Oh, it was... it was something and a young man was...

601
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:06,000
I think this West Side story was something.

602
01:02:06,000 --> 01:02:08,000
Oh, yes, yeah.

603
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:11,000
Oh, my... I don't remember the details that...

604
01:02:11,000 --> 01:02:15,000
Somebody... one of your friends at the meeting was...

605
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:18,000
At the movie was taken out and beaten and put in jail.

606
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:19,000
I'm sorry. I just...

607
01:02:19,000 --> 01:02:22,000
Well, maybe... maybe somebody has made that up.

608
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:25,000
I don't know. It couldn't happen.

609
01:02:25,000 --> 01:02:28,000
But I do remember going to the movie.

610
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:32,000
And at that time, you know, integration was just...

611
01:02:32,000 --> 01:02:35,000
Yeah, you know, beginning to take hold and...

612
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:38,000
But still kind of... you know...

613
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:43,000
Well, in Greenwood, of course, they had the McGhee brothers, you know,

614
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:50,000
they were integrating theaters and getting beaten up and all kinds of instances.

615
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:56,000
One of the major things to come out of the summer project or Freedom Summer was

616
01:02:56,000 --> 01:02:59,000
the challenge of the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party,

617
01:02:59,000 --> 01:03:05,000
which was challenging the legitimacy of the regular segregationist delegation

618
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:08,000
at the National Convention in Atlantic City.

619
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:14,000
Talk a little bit about FDP and your relation to it and your thoughts.

620
01:03:14,000 --> 01:03:18,000
Oh, the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party.

621
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:24,000
Well, as everybody knows, by now,

622
01:03:25,000 --> 01:03:31,000
if black people couldn't vote, they couldn't participate in the democratic process.

623
01:03:31,000 --> 01:03:40,000
And so the Democratic Party from Mississippi was almost always an all-white delegation.

624
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:48,000
And this... Freedom Democratic Party was formed and it was made up of a cross-section of individuals,

625
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:52,000
you know, to kind of reflect the makeup of the state.

626
01:03:52,000 --> 01:03:59,000
And when we went to Atlantic City, I was not actually, you know,

627
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:04,000
an official part of the delegation, but I went along, I took a bus,

628
01:04:04,000 --> 01:04:06,000
and I think Miss Hayden was on that bus.

629
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:08,000
Well, we'll talk about your experience there of this.

630
01:04:08,000 --> 01:04:09,000
Okay.

631
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:11,000
I didn't know that you were there.

632
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:12,000
Oh, I actually went.

633
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:13,000
Oh, okay.

634
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:18,000
So we wrote a bus up to Atlantic City.

635
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:23,000
And when we got there, of course we couldn't go in.

636
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:28,000
We spent most of our time, you know, just outside the convention center there.

637
01:04:28,000 --> 01:04:35,000
But I remember that when a few people were allowed in,

638
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:38,000
then we would share the badges.

639
01:04:38,000 --> 01:04:41,000
And so to allow as many people as possible,

640
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:43,000
oh, if you could go in at a time.

641
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:45,000
So the badges were shared.

642
01:04:45,000 --> 01:04:48,000
We had a couple of things to go in for just a few minutes.

643
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:52,000
And we heard about Miss Hayden's testimony.

644
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:56,000
And what President Johnson did, you know,

645
01:04:56,000 --> 01:05:00,000
when she was given that really, really powerful testimony.

646
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:01,000
Called a press conference.

647
01:05:01,000 --> 01:05:04,000
Called a press conference to get her off the air.

648
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:09,000
But most of our time was just spent, you know, just being there

649
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:12,000
and being outside, being on the boardwalk,

650
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:17,000
sometimes singing freedom songs and just giving our support.

651
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:22,000
Were you talking to people or was that mainly members of the delegation

652
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:24,000
that we're talking to others?

653
01:05:24,000 --> 01:05:27,000
It was mainly members of the delegation.

654
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:32,000
What was the mood there that did, was there for a time after Mrs. Hamer's emotional testimony?

655
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:34,000
Did you think you were going to win?

656
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:35,000
We thought so.

657
01:05:35,000 --> 01:05:36,000
We thought so.

658
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:40,000
But, you know, then these factions developed.

659
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:46,000
You know, of course, there were people who wanted to accept the compromise.

660
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:48,000
Which was two seats at large.

661
01:05:48,000 --> 01:05:50,000
At large, two seats.

662
01:05:50,000 --> 01:06:00,000
And Miss Haymer and Annie Devine" and maybe Victoria Gray.

663
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:04,000
And these women, you know, said no.

664
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:06,000
No, we don't want two seats.

665
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:08,000
I mean, Miss Haymer said, we don't need two seats.

666
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:09,000
Two seats.

667
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:10,000
One of us is tied.

668
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:14,000
So she was against accepting the compromise.

669
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:17,000
And there were a couple people who were not a couple.

670
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:21,000
There were a lot of people who wanted to accept the compromise.

671
01:06:21,000 --> 01:06:29,000
And so, at that point, I think a rift developed between the,

672
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:40,000
mostly the rural activists who had been down in the trenches really working for, and they

673
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:42,240
were working for more than just a compromise.

674
01:06:42,240 --> 01:06:44,240
I didn't think it was fair.

675
01:06:44,240 --> 01:06:48,520
I didn't think it was the right thing to do to see an all-white delegation and just

676
01:06:48,520 --> 01:06:57,520
offer the Democrats who had a composition that was more of what the state was made up of.

677
01:06:57,520 --> 01:07:03,400
What was it like on the bus coming back?

678
01:07:03,400 --> 01:07:05,440
Did you, were you depressed?

679
01:07:05,440 --> 01:07:07,840
Did you think you'd made your point?

680
01:07:07,840 --> 01:07:09,640
Were you eager to get back in the field?

681
01:07:09,640 --> 01:07:13,560
Oh, I was eager to get back.

682
01:07:13,560 --> 01:07:19,520
At this point, let's say this is 1964.

683
01:07:19,520 --> 01:07:27,480
And you know, after the summer of 1964, things kind of, you know, we were kind of

684
01:07:27,480 --> 01:07:33,480
what, do we weren't sure about the direction that we were going to go in?

685
01:07:33,480 --> 01:07:38,920
And things just kind of started to, you know, to kind of fall apart in the movement.

686
01:07:38,920 --> 01:07:41,800
We lost the focus, okay.

687
01:07:41,800 --> 01:07:47,360
You know, the voting, I mean, the Civil Rights Act, you know, I think at that point,

688
01:07:47,360 --> 01:07:49,720
you were passed, okay.

689
01:07:49,720 --> 01:07:53,200
And then the following year, though, the Voting Rights Act was passed.

690
01:07:53,200 --> 01:07:54,800
So it's September of 1964.

691
01:07:54,800 --> 01:07:55,800
What are you doing?

692
01:07:55,800 --> 01:08:00,400
I decided to, it was time for me to go ahead and go to college.

693
01:08:00,400 --> 01:08:07,520
And so I enrolled in, and into the college along with several other people, Glenn Gillen,

694
01:08:07,520 --> 01:08:13,640
Hollis Watkins, MacArthur Cotton, and a bunch of other people.

695
01:08:13,640 --> 01:08:16,880
We were in a work state program.

696
01:08:16,880 --> 01:08:20,600
So our tuition was paid, you know.

697
01:08:20,600 --> 01:08:24,880
And so you're focused then shifted more to education after that?

698
01:08:24,880 --> 01:08:28,280
And you're focused on making it shifted to education.

699
01:08:28,280 --> 01:08:32,480
Tell us something about Tougaloo when you were there.

700
01:08:32,480 --> 01:08:35,080
Well let me tell you, I first heard about Tougaloo.

701
01:08:35,080 --> 01:08:39,560
I had no idea what Tougaloo was until, because I was away from here.

702
01:08:39,560 --> 01:08:41,360
So I didn't know anything about the colleges.

703
01:08:41,360 --> 01:08:45,640
I knew about Valley, that's where I'm from, Mississippi Valley State University.

704
01:08:45,640 --> 01:08:52,360
But then one day we had a career day at Amanda Elzy High School, that's a school day.

705
01:08:52,360 --> 01:08:57,720
Now that was a consolidated school that I went to that was right outside of Greenwood.

706
01:08:57,720 --> 01:09:04,920
And we had a representative from several colleges and Tougaloo College was one of the places.

707
01:09:04,920 --> 01:09:08,480
And the man was, he was a foreigner.

708
01:09:08,480 --> 01:09:12,040
He's a black man, but he spoke French.

709
01:09:12,040 --> 01:09:16,120
And he had this wonderful accent.

710
01:09:16,120 --> 01:09:21,360
And he talked about Tougaloo in such glowing terms.

711
01:09:21,360 --> 01:09:25,720
But you know what, I had heard about Tougaloo College, which I forgot.

712
01:09:25,720 --> 01:09:27,240
Because I'm going to tell you this.

713
01:09:27,240 --> 01:09:32,480
When I was growing up, I heard a lot about my great grandfather from my mother.

714
01:09:32,480 --> 01:09:37,320
She said, it's in the family that he actually, that he went to Tougaloo College.

715
01:09:37,320 --> 01:09:41,480
Yes, I've got a picture of my great-grandmother upstairs.

716
01:09:41,480 --> 01:09:47,040
And on the back of it, my mother, it was always fun to write stuff on the back of pictures.

717
01:09:47,040 --> 01:09:50,400
She's got written down, I'll show it to you when we're done.

718
01:09:50,440 --> 01:09:54,760
Professor, she called it Professor Jeff Davis.

719
01:09:54,760 --> 01:09:56,360
Jeff Davis, can you believe it?

720
01:09:56,360 --> 01:09:57,760
Pearson.

721
01:09:57,760 --> 01:10:03,080
And she said he was, he went to Tougaloo College and she lists all his wife, Georgia.

722
01:10:03,080 --> 01:10:05,280
That's the picture of my great-grandmother.

723
01:10:05,280 --> 01:10:11,280
And all of their children, one of his children was my grandmother, his daughter,

724
01:10:11,280 --> 01:10:12,040
birth of Pearson.

725
01:10:12,040 --> 01:10:18,360
And what he did was that he educated, he'd now also have some great-on schools who went to college.

726
01:10:18,360 --> 01:10:21,560
One was in a accountant and one did something else.

727
01:10:21,560 --> 01:10:23,040
That's very unusual.

728
01:10:23,040 --> 01:10:25,440
Very unusual, which I have to remember the times.

729
01:10:25,440 --> 01:10:28,480
This was like that first and second generation.

730
01:10:28,480 --> 01:10:29,960
This was the reconstruction.

731
01:10:29,960 --> 01:10:31,560
When there were possibilities.

732
01:10:31,560 --> 01:10:32,680
Yes, yes.

733
01:10:32,680 --> 01:10:37,320
And so they were educated and they owned land and everything.

734
01:10:37,320 --> 01:10:44,440
And was that generation, my mother's generation, after they lost everything and went back to that system,

735
01:10:44,440 --> 01:10:49,400
well, went into that system, the Jim Crow and the sharecropping and all that.

736
01:10:49,400 --> 01:10:55,400
And my mother just was, when she grew up, she was, you know, she was very sheltered from

737
01:10:55,400 --> 01:10:57,200
the racism and whatever.

738
01:10:57,200 --> 01:11:03,400
And then she married my father, and she got thrown into this world that she knew nothing about.

739
01:11:03,400 --> 01:11:04,760
But anyway, where were we?

740
01:11:04,760 --> 01:11:06,480
I was talking about something else.

741
01:11:06,480 --> 01:11:09,680
Well, we were talking about being at Tougaloo.

742
01:11:09,680 --> 01:11:10,880
Being at Tougaloo.

743
01:11:10,880 --> 01:11:13,840
What it was like in 64, 65.

744
01:11:13,840 --> 01:11:18,720
Well, in 1964, Tougaloo, well, Tougaloo was a really different place from that.

745
01:11:18,720 --> 01:11:25,920
Tougaloo had this history of being this oasis for the movement.

746
01:11:25,920 --> 01:11:26,920
Private school.

747
01:11:26,920 --> 01:11:31,440
Private school, small, private school.

748
01:11:31,440 --> 01:11:41,680
And it had the reputation of really educating people and turning out people who would go on to be

749
01:11:41,680 --> 01:11:44,080
lawyers and doctors and whatever.

750
01:11:44,080 --> 01:11:46,120
And I wanted so badly to go to Tougaloo.

751
01:11:46,120 --> 01:11:48,960
I just didn't think my parents could afford to send them.

752
01:11:48,960 --> 01:11:54,400
But then, after being involved in the movement of someone arranged for scholarships for

753
01:11:54,400 --> 01:11:55,880
those of us who wanted to go.

754
01:11:55,880 --> 01:12:00,400
And so maybe ten of us actually went, started to Tougaloo.

755
01:12:00,400 --> 01:12:01,400
So I went to Tougaloo.

756
01:12:01,400 --> 01:12:06,800
But then I got married the following early in 65.

757
01:12:06,800 --> 01:12:09,680
I got married.

758
01:12:09,680 --> 01:12:11,000
And I started having children.

759
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:16,080
So I went to Tougaloo for two years, half summer.

760
01:12:16,080 --> 01:12:17,400
What was it like here?

761
01:12:17,400 --> 01:12:23,040
You were all hard in movement veterans and you're at a school with a bunch of kids who,

762
01:12:23,040 --> 01:12:24,600
most of whom have not had.

763
01:12:24,600 --> 01:12:33,240
It was really difficult to settle down and to, you know, to get involved, to try to get

764
01:12:33,240 --> 01:12:37,200
involved in campus life, as a matter of fact, I never really really did.

765
01:12:37,200 --> 01:12:40,800
I just felt so removed from that.

766
01:12:40,800 --> 01:12:46,360
I mean, I went to my classes and I did what I had to do in terms of my studies, but I

767
01:12:46,360 --> 01:12:49,640
didn't get involved much in the campus life.

768
01:12:49,640 --> 01:12:53,040
Except for, you know, I made a few friends.

769
01:12:53,040 --> 01:12:55,560
Okay.

770
01:12:55,560 --> 01:13:03,200
So it was just, it was really hard to make the transition from, have it been involved

771
01:13:03,200 --> 01:13:04,200
in the movement.

772
01:13:04,200 --> 01:13:06,720
I mean, I went to the March on Washington, right?

773
01:13:06,720 --> 01:13:13,040
I'd met Martin Luther King, Stokely Carmichael, and all these people who had been involved

774
01:13:13,040 --> 01:13:14,040
in the movement.

775
01:13:14,040 --> 01:13:18,080
It was just a wonderful, exhilarating, exciting time.

776
01:13:18,080 --> 01:13:25,520
And then to leave that and to come back and to move into a whole other world, the academic

777
01:13:25,520 --> 01:13:32,720
world, when most of the students there, the girls were trying to get into sororities

778
01:13:32,720 --> 01:13:35,640
and the boys, I never did get involved in that.

779
01:13:35,640 --> 01:13:39,160
I just didn't see the point of it.

780
01:13:39,160 --> 01:13:44,120
And so it just happened at a time in my life when I had no interest in doing that.

781
01:13:44,120 --> 01:13:46,080
I'm not saying that it's a bad thing.

782
01:13:46,080 --> 01:13:53,360
It's just that it was just something that I didn't want to do after having been involved

783
01:13:53,360 --> 01:13:55,000
in the movement.

784
01:13:55,000 --> 01:13:58,120
So it was, but it was a good experience.

785
01:13:58,120 --> 01:14:03,920
I made some life-long friends or Tougaloo, like, it, Tougaloo was like a family,

786
01:14:03,920 --> 01:14:06,160
a community in itself, right?

787
01:14:06,160 --> 01:14:08,520
No professors do you remember?

788
01:14:08,520 --> 01:14:09,840
Oh gosh.

789
01:14:09,840 --> 01:14:19,520
I remember, oh my goodness, well, Dr. Naomi Townsend, oh, look, great Dr. Naomi Townsend,

790
01:14:19,520 --> 01:14:24,520
I was in her class, and she had an upper level, I don't know how I got into that English

791
01:14:24,520 --> 01:14:26,640
class, sorry.

792
01:14:26,640 --> 01:14:28,480
And boy, she was strict.

793
01:14:28,480 --> 01:14:34,920
At that point, girls could not wear pants to her class.

794
01:14:34,920 --> 01:14:36,400
I didn't know that.

795
01:14:36,400 --> 01:14:39,160
So I wear pants all the time, right?

796
01:14:39,160 --> 01:14:44,000
I mean, my uniform was jeans for the last couple of years.

797
01:14:44,000 --> 01:14:45,640
And you could wear pants to chapel.

798
01:14:45,640 --> 01:14:48,120
We had to go to chapel, you know, once a week.

799
01:14:48,120 --> 01:14:54,000
I stepped in the Dr. Townsend's class one day and she said, Miss Simpson, I will have

800
01:14:54,000 --> 01:14:56,160
to see you after class.

801
01:14:56,160 --> 01:14:59,120
And everybody started looking me, they knew what was coming, right?

802
01:14:59,120 --> 01:15:06,300
And so she blessed me up and down about you do not come to my class with slack so I

803
01:15:06,300 --> 01:15:08,880
don't know Dr. Townsend.

804
01:15:08,880 --> 01:15:15,540
And then I cut my hair and I was wearing an afro and she said, and another thing, why

805
01:15:15,540 --> 01:15:18,440
do you have to wear your hair like that?

806
01:15:18,440 --> 01:15:22,960
Can't you just, you know, I mean, you're on a college campus now.

807
01:15:22,960 --> 01:15:24,560
Can't you do better than that?

808
01:15:24,560 --> 01:15:26,640
And of course, I ignored her.

809
01:15:26,640 --> 01:15:27,640
That was early on.

810
01:15:27,640 --> 01:15:28,880
There were not many afros.

811
01:15:28,880 --> 01:15:32,240
No, not many afros in 64.

812
01:15:32,240 --> 01:15:39,360
And then on top of that, I used to ride a motorcycle, a tiny little, little white Honda

813
01:15:39,360 --> 01:15:43,160
motorcycle because I lived in Jackson for about a time.

814
01:15:43,160 --> 01:15:45,400
And it's six miles out.

815
01:15:45,400 --> 01:15:47,320
Exactly.

816
01:15:47,320 --> 01:15:53,720
So I tell you there was some notoriety there among the, all the movement people.

817
01:15:53,720 --> 01:15:57,960
I don't know why it was that we were, you know, why we stood out so much because of

818
01:15:57,960 --> 01:15:59,800
the reputation that Tougaloo had of it.

819
01:15:59,800 --> 01:16:04,800
You know, the Tougaloo 9 had been there and it had been very open and we, you know, receptive

820
01:16:04,800 --> 01:16:05,800
to the movement.

821
01:16:05,800 --> 01:16:12,280
I mean, we were accepted and got along well with our classmates.

822
01:16:12,280 --> 01:16:18,800
My experience was, and reading also was that Tougaloo could mobilize its students, get

823
01:16:18,800 --> 01:16:22,640
